text: Good evening all hope you all had a great x mas and a happy new year to you all . Just after a bit of information if at all possible. I'm wondering how many of you adorable maine coon owners have had any health issues with your fur babies? The reason I ask as that I've seen a few post with hip operations but I also read that other possible health issues could include hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, hip dysplasia and spinal muscular atrophy. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is the most common I hear. I currently own a grey tabby moggie of approx 17 months and our British shorthair of 12 weeks both adorable and were finishing off with a must have black smoke male maine coon. He's currently approx 7 weeks old and due to pick him up mid February. Can't wait! . The breeder states both parents are health checked but is there anything else we could do to try and prevent any health issues? I look forward to your knowledge and hopefully positive feedback. Here is a pic of our current cats and then a recent one of our black smoke üòä üòª üòª

text: RIP in Belle. We will miss you, Sassy Girl! Belle has been battling cancer since August. Today, she went to the vet for her weekly treatment and was happy and a little sassy.  She even made a new friend at the vet who was having their Golden Retriever looked at by the vet. This evening, she went to her kennel to lie down (her safe place), and she quietly and peacefully passed away. 7/16/20 - 01/04/24 - Way too young.

text: My 6 yr old (just turned 6 Dec 27th) golden Storm was just diagnosed with intermediate-large cell lymphoma. Currently waiting on PCR test results to find out what type it is and schedule appt with Oncologist.All her lymph nodes are swollen the size of golf balls. Has not spread internally so we caught it in early stages. She is starting to have slight difficulty swallowing her dry kibble. We are going to start cooking her food at home. She has chicken allergy so we will be using ground turkey, lamb and beef liver. ( she hates fish/salmon). Brown rice,oatmeal,carrots, green veggies,blueberries,apples.I just need some guidance/reassurance with anyone‚Äôs personal experience going through something similar with their babies. Already ordered multivitamins,digestive enzymes,calcium powder and turkey tail supplements. Am I missing anything? I just want to help her the best we can.

text: Hi everyone, My 2 year old golden retriever is acting very down, not lethargic. Last night he had the runs, and then this morning ate half his meal and refused his supper. We had an issue last month with similar but worse behaviour, where he was feeling down, not eating, pooping but drinking water. Last time we assumed he ate something as he has done this a couple times. He is monitored closely and crated when we are away. When we took him to the vet his mood lifted but we tested him for several issues anyways. It turned out he had a liver infection and may have had a UTI. Meds and gastro food for the next week helped bring him back to normal. We are going to monitor him until tomorrow and then determine if we are taking him back to the vet. Any one had this happen before? What could it be? More liver tests? I‚Äôd like to have some sort of direction or idea before we go back to the vet so we don‚Äôt aimlessly run tests and another large vet bill. Thanks, Caroline and her golden, Reggie.  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/415604520_10163397459114968_3732745689218613804_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p526x296&_nc_cat=110&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=_ZUecsENqP8AX8l_MaX&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfDrC6d4RzvIF5bLc_pziKyCChgpxT7tjYrrfhsdD2dp7Q&oe=659C2876

text: This is Story of a Golden Retriever that may be harboring a secret identity... I have frequently posted about Bo,our bestest boy , and his pack mates, Cammie the Lab, Rusty Jones, and Coco. Last night, late, all was quiet as I got ready to jump in the shower. Then came this noise...a howl, much more than that really, the most prolonged ,from the depths of hell howl that literally sent chills down my spine! I ran to the living room and said to my hubby "WHAT WAS THAT????" He said "Bo". Bo was sound asleep like nothing had happened, but I was shook. Tom ( hubby) said if the lights had been off, he would have **** himself. I told him what I had heard was Hounds of Hell, Werewolf shit!!!!!!! Bo has never howled in the 4 years we've had him. I checked for a full moon, cause I'm on to Bo now. I finished getting ready for bed, went through the kitchen, grabbed a head of garlic, and offered a few cloves to my husband, just in case. I realize now that garlic is geared more towards Vampires, but I wasn't taking any chances. Good Night everybody, I said. If you need me, just yell. It will take me a minute to unlock the door and push the dresser out of the way to get to you, but I'll come.  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/415503741_3664053943842361_8000562139503550533_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p526x296&_nc_cat=108&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=ziUSIHiubWMAX93SWFl&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfA9GcDWW0dK9ceCvdkR6VboSM_rK6e0C5HOF6I9MM2QFw&oe=659D7DBE

text: *****Advice***** Our shadow girl just turned 9. She's been through a lot in the last year with a major surgery and an infection. About a year and a half ago she had 2 seizures. About 6 months later She had another too. The vet said they wouldn't recommend putting her on medication because they weren't super frequent and so spaced out. While at work on New Year's Eve I found out that she had a small one and then a really bad 10 minutes after. Thinking it had been 6 months since her last 2 I figured we'd be in the clear. Unfortunately I woke up at 7 AM About an hour ago to her having another one it wasn't bad and she came out of it within 2 minutes. It was the kind where she was stiff but not shaking like crazy I was able to calmly talk her out of it and she immediately started acting like a puppy. I will be getting her into the next week if there's an appointment available. The advice I'm asking is for other golden parents that have anything like this going on what kind of medication or things do you use that you have noticed a significant difference or has helped. And does anybody else having these type of issues. Wondering if anybody has used CBD oils or drops to help calm them down when this happens.  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/417004239_10224676536442816_3509269999207911111_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_s1080x2048&_nc_cat=110&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=NC46bRvKA-kAX9i7EXM&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfCnnXsTrE8yTRUp7WDHD6MnPMDKiP3Ai40X_uIV0cbpxQ&oe=659CD74D

text: The Daily Dolly. The ongoing tale of our beautiful rescue Goldie, HRH Princess Dolly Lazar.  Our poor little Princess was not very well yesterday.  It started on Sunday night - she kept drinking lots of water and then retching.  She had us up several times that night to go outside where she kept trying to be sick but was only producing clear/frothy liquid.  She rather gingerly ate some breakfast yesterday and seemed OK on her walk but then was very lethargic and continued to drink lots of water, after which she would try to be sick.  We were concerned it might be bloat but her stomach did not feel at all distended, her gums were not pale and she did not appear to be in pain.  Of course being New Year's Day the vet was closed so we decided to monitor her and get her to an emergency vet if necessary.  She remained very listless all day and Dylan was so sweet and gentle with her, lying beside her most of the day and not trying to indulge in any rough and tumble - such a good and sensitive pup!  I made her some scrambled egg and whole grain rice in the evening which she enjoyed and I'm pleased to say kept down.  She slept through the night and enjoyed some more egg and rice for breakfast and now seems OK.  Fingers crossed! Such a worry when they are ill!  https://scontent-cdg4-2.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/413002756_6820152908082942_4438047568167804008_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p180x540&_nc_cat=103&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=qHLaQscQXSMAX-aOkbo&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-2.xx&oh=00_AfArqe3SjR7te6TVmyDbk8xlG7l2xUJhzCl1f2Sj4S5Tdw&oe=659DCDEA

text: One may ask why is your one year old golden so tired??  The answer is because he has taken on a very very big job! My daughter has had health issues since birth(now 24) we recently found out she needs a double organ transplant(liver and pancreas)! Well Oliver has taken on the role of protector and  blood sugar inspector through the night, (he has not been trained he is our pet). Somehow Oliver knows when Kylie Giel is in trouble and he will relentlessly try to wake me up and forces his way into her bedroom when her sugar is unstable, he will paw, whine, and bite her hand until she is up and addressing whatever issue is going on! Some may not believe our story but this isn‚Äôt the first time! Oliver has been acting strangely around kylie since September when her health nightmare started. He has always spent the night in our bedroom since he came home but starting in September he now goes in Kylie‚Äôs bedroom until she is up for the day when no one else is home. Oliver will not leave Kylie‚Äôs bed until she does! Dogs are a gift and angels on earth! So thankful for this guy! He has a rough job but he is amazing at it!!!
author: Jayme Giel

text: Fortaleza, 02 January 2024 ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä Dear Diary, ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä Of course I have to suffer in the very first day of the year. To start I had to put up with mom gawking at me  because I snored through the fireworks of midnight and the thunder storm in the middle of the night, but jumped off my bed growling because she sneezed. And to make matters worse she sneezed the whole day. She made fun of me for going crazy and getting scared of sneezes. How dare her?!? She is scared of big and medium fish and marine mammals even away from the water! Ms Kettle if you ask me. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä Actually, she has been making fun of me for days, saying I‚Äôm a really poor excuse for a gun dog, and all because I let a weird looking and grumpy bird attack her. While I have to admit wild animals seem to be out to get us in general, that bird was particularly crazy and mean. Really, we were just sitting there existing, and that thing just flipped and attacked us. I was the first victim. The bird came at my head but gave up after I jumped a couple of times to snatch it out of the air. It went after mom then. Since she is sort of crazy I figured she could handle herself. I was wrong. She just freaked out and told me to keep that extra from The Birds by Hitchcock away from her. When I just sat on my haunches and watched the show she was pretty offended and I had to walk all the way back to the car listening to her mumbling ‚Äúbird dog my foot‚Äù and other things along those lines. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä Since mom decided to work the bare minimum, there were a lot of things we did not do this month. One of them was getting a Xmas tree. Mom said she was not up to spend the whole month cleaning fur off the tree to keep it looking beautiful. We also did not go out anywhere other than for our walks because there is a heat wave frying our country and mom refuses to leave the house for anything other than the absolute necessary and only if air conditioning is involved. I did get a nice meal on Christmas Eve and a really nice looking bunny. New Year‚Äôs Eve was calm because mom does not celebrate it, but there was a great meal for me and wine for her. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä I have high hopes for the new year. Hopefully, I can come up with new ways to embrace mom but not hurt her. I‚Äôm off, she is sneezing again and it is freaking me out. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä Bites, ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä Shark

text: Princess Dolly would like to say a big thank you to all our FB friends who have sent so many good wishes today.  I am pleased to say she is now feeling much better.  We have let her rest today and didn't walk her in the horrible weather, although crazy Dylan enjoyed it!  He has been really sweet with her the whole time which is so lovely to see.  More scrambled eggs and wholegrain rice again this evening then hopefully back to a normal diet again tomorrow.  We think she must have picked up and eaten something on her Sunday walk that upset her tummy.  Hopefully nothing more serious than that.  We always hate seeing her in any sort of distress or discomfort particularly considering her awful life prior to her coming to us from Serbia in 2018. text: I just wanted to share some good news we‚Äôve gotten. Wesley here is five years old, and in October, he was diagnosed with IMHA. Luckily, we caught it early and did not have to do any blood transfusions. But this poor little guy has been on prednisone since. He‚Äôs been hungry, hot, and thirsty. He‚Äôs had lethargic days and weeks where he just looked down and like he was so uncomfortable. He was normally a happy go lucky boy. He‚Äôs heen struggling with PCV numbers in the 30s, on the low end of the average range. Luckily we have bloodwork done at every annual, so we knew he was low for his personal average. Well, on Friday, he got another check, and he‚Äôs up to 47%! He‚Äôs doing so much better lately and starting to act like his normal self. We‚Äôre still working on weaning off prednisone, but we‚Äôre just so happy right now. Also so grateful to our regular vet and ER vet for diagnosing and treating him. Poor little guy is terrified of the vet, but he‚Äôs done a good job going in every two weeks. We‚Äôve got another appointment in two weeks then hoping we will have to go less. üíô üíô üíô  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/415811123_10224958040553610_5882313749439265046_n.jpg?stp=cp6_dst-jpg_p526x296&_nc_cat=108&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=Pyy48YOOVSMAX_VIz2P&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfBUCo2utADqOQRX39iiVf-St9Qa6FWVwClrE4WjKxtAQA&oe=659D91A2

text: Hi friends! I have a beautiful 9mo golden, this post is not about her. Just needing some advice. There is a couple I am friends with who recently adopted a rottie. He‚Äôs a big cutie, but knowing them I knew he wouldn‚Äôt be well trained so I told my partner that our girl will not be meeting him. (Dog mom intuition lol) My boyfriend spends more time with the couple than I do, and the other week he was at their place and got bit on the mouth. The dog was not trying be aggressive, more just nippy as he is stilll a puppy, but he did get my bf pretty good. The parents are apologetic but don‚Äôt really do much other than say he doesn‚Äôt know his own strength. Then last night, we were over again and the pup chomped on our friends hand pretty hard. He was bleeding and again not much happened with the dog besides putting him up. We want to approach a conversation with these dog parents as their friends to express our concerns that they need to put this powerful dog in training before something worse happens, but are unsure of how to start that conversation without coming off too aggressive to where they shut down and won‚Äôt listen. PLEASE remember to be kind and try to not be judgmental. Remember: we‚Äôre trying to help people and pups not shame them.
